&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AD bisects &amp;ang;BAC&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AB = AC&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AD is common in both triangles&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If two sides and the included angle of one triangle are equal to the corresponding two sides and included angle of another triangle, then triangles are congruent (SAS rule).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/qImage69a18d3be53cac99ef69641e.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 301px; width: 350px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; AB = AC&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; &amp;ang;BAD = &amp;ang;CAD&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; AD = AD&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Two sides and included angle are equal&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; △ABD &amp;cong; △ACD by SAS rule&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;there4; The correct answer is Yes, by SAS rule.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Area of triangle ABC = 60&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;G is centroid&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Medians divide triangle into 6 equal area triangles&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Area of triangle formed by centroid and two vertices = (1 &amp;divide; 3) &amp;times; Total area&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/qImage69a42451850f6364ad6101a9.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 244px; width: 300px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Total area = 60&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Area of each small triangle = 60 &amp;divide; 6&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Area of each small triangle = 10&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Triangle GBC consists of 2 small triangles&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Area of triangle GBC = 2 &amp;times; 10&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Area of triangle GBC = 20&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;there4; The correct answer is 20 cm&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Diameter of circle = 10 cm&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AC = 10 cm&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AB = 6 cm&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ang;B = 90&amp;deg;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In a right triangle, (Leg)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = Hypotenuse &amp;times; Projection of that leg on hypotenuse&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/qImage69a0a82ffcec28499aa63988.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 336px; width: 350px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; AB&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = AC &amp;times; AD&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 6&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = 10 &amp;times; AD&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 36 = 10 &amp;times; AD&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; AD = 36 &amp;divide; 10&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; AD = 3.6 cm&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;there4; The correct answer is 3.6 cm.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ang;B = 90&amp;deg;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ang;E = 90&amp;deg;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hypotenuse AC = Hypotenuse DF&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Side AB = Side DE&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formula Used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;RHS Congruence Rule&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If in two right-angled triangles, hypotenuse and one corresponding side are equal, then the triangles are congruent&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Both triangles are right-angled&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Hypotenuse AC = DF&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; One corresponding side AB = DE&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; Condition of RHS rule satisfied&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;there4; The triangles are congruent by RHS rule.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
